In .NET 10, Android's `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` is fully deprecated and MAUI no longer honors `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize`. The replacement is a combination of **edge-to-edge insets** and MAUI's built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`.

## Quick fix — use `adjustResize` in the manifest + proper layout

**1. AndroidManifest.xml** — keep `adjustResize` (it still works on most devices even though it's deprecated at the API level):

```xml
<activity ... android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" />
```

**2. Structure your page so the input is inside a Grid that fills the screen:**

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" />
    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

## If `adjustResize` still isn't working (common on Android 15+ / edge-to-edge)

Disable MAUI's auto-scroll and handle insets yourself:

**On the Entry or the page:**
```xml
<Entry KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect="True" ... />
```

**In your Android platform code** (`Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`):

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
}

private class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

        // Bottom padding = max of keyboard or nav bar
        v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom));

        return insets;
    }
}
```

This makes the entire window content shrink when the keyboard opens, pushing your input bar up — the modern equivalent of the old Resize mode.

## TL;DR

| Approach | When to use |
|----------|-------------|
| `adjustResize` in manifest | Works on most devices through Android 14 |
| `WindowInsets` listener | Required for Android 15+ edge-to-edge |
| `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (default) | Fine for forms; unreliable for bottom-anchored chat UIs |

For a chat screen, the **WindowInsets** approach is the most reliable path forward.
